children.comments:
The `Foldable` instance is best used with a *commutative*
function/`Monoid`, since hash maps do not guarantee any
particular order.
children.title: foldableHashMap

children.comments:
The `FoldableWithIndex` instance is best used with a
*commutative* function/`Monoid`, since hash maps do not guarantee
any particular order.
children.title: foldableWithIndexHashMap

declarations.comments:
Immutable hash maps from keys `k` to values `v`.

Note that this is an *unordered* collection.
declarations.title: HashMap

declarations.comments: The empty map.
declarations.title: empty

declarations.comments:
A map of one key and its associated value.

`singleton k v == insert k v empty`
declarations.title: singleton

declarations.comments: Get a value by key.
declarations.title: lookup

declarations.comments:
Insert or replace a value.

`lookup k (insert k v m) == Just v`
declarations.title: insert

declarations.comments:
Remove a key and its associated value from a map.

`lookup k (delete k m) == Nothing`
declarations.title: delete

declarations.comments:
Returns the number of key-value pairs in a map.

`size (singleton k v) == 1`
declarations.title: size

declarations.comments:
Test whether a map is empty.

`isEmpty m  ==  (m == empty)`
declarations.title: isEmpty

declarations.comments: Test whether a key is in a map.
declarations.title: member

declarations.comments:
Insert a new value if it doesn't exist or update the existing
value by applying a function to it.

If you need to combine the new value with the existing value
consider using `insertWith` instead.
declarations.title: upsert

declarations.comments:
Insert the new value if the key doesn't exist, otherwise combine
the existing and new values.

The combining function is called with the existing value as the
first argument and the new value as the second argument.

```PureScript
insertWith (<>) 5 "b" (singleton 5 "a") == singleton 5 "ab"
```

If your update function does not use the existing value, consider
using `upsert` instead.
declarations.title: insertWith

declarations.comments: Update or delete the value for a key in a map.
declarations.title: update

declarations.comments: Insert a value, delete a value, or update a value for a key in a map.
declarations.title: alter

declarations.comments:
Remove key-value-pairs from a map for which the predicate does
not hold.

```PureScript
filter (const False) m == empty
filter (const True) m == m
```
declarations.title: filter

declarations.comments:
Remove key-value-pairs from a map for which the predicate does
not hold.

Like `filter`, but the predicate takes both key and value.
declarations.title: filterWithKey

declarations.comments:
Remove all keys from the map for which the predicate does not
hold.

`difference m1 m2 == filterKeys (\k -> member k m2) m1`
declarations.title: filterKeys

declarations.comments:
Apply a function to all values in a hash map, discard the
`Nothing` results, and keep the value of the `Just` results.
declarations.title: mapMaybe

declarations.comments:
Apply a function to all key value pairs in a hash map, discard
the `Nothing` results, and keep the value of the `Just` results.
declarations.title: mapMaybeWithKey

declarations.comments:
Turn an array of pairs into a hash map.

This uses a mutable hash map internally and is faster than
`fromFoldable`.

If you have an array of something other than tuples, use
`fromArrayBy`.
declarations.title: fromArray

declarations.comments:
Turn a foldable functor of pairs into a hash map.

In the presence of duplicate keys, later (by `foldl`) mappings
overwrite earlier mappings.

If your input is an array, consider using `fromArray` instead.
declarations.title: fromFoldable

declarations.comments:
Turn an array into a hash map given extraction functions for keys
and values.

This uses a mutable hash map internally and is faster than
`fromFoldable` and `fromFoldableBy`.
declarations.title: fromArrayBy

declarations.comments:
Turn a foldable functor into a hash map given extraction
functions for keys and values.

If your input is an array, consider using `fromArrayBy` instead.

`fromFoldableBy fst snd == fromFoldable`
declarations.title: fromFoldableBy

declarations.comments:
Turn a foldable functor with index into a hash map.

This can be used to convert, for example, an ordered map into a
hash map with the same keys and values, or an array into a hash
map with values indexed by their position in the array.

```PureScript
fromFoldableWithIndex ["a", "b"] == fromArray [Tuple 0 "a", Tuple 1 "b"]
```
declarations.title: fromFoldableWithIndex

declarations.comments:
Convert a map to an array using the given function.

Note that no particular order is guaranteed.

```PureScript
toArrayBy Tuple (singleton 1 2) == [Tuple 1 2]
toArrayBy const        m == keys m
toArrayBy (flip const) m == values m
```
declarations.title: toArrayBy

declarations.comments:
Returns the keys of the map in no particular order.

If you need both keys and values, use `toArrayBy` rather than
both `keys` and `values`.
declarations.title: keys

declarations.comments:
Returns the values of the map in no particular order.

If you need both keys and values, use `toArrayBy` rather than
both `keys` and `values`.
declarations.title: values

declarations.comments:
Union two maps.

For duplicate keys, we keep the value from the left map.
declarations.title: union

declarations.comments:
Union two maps, combining the values for keys that appear in both maps using the given function.

`unionWith (-) (singleton 0 3) (singleton 0 2) == singleton 0 1`
declarations.title: unionWith

declarations.comments: Intersect two maps.
declarations.title: intersection

declarations.comments:
Intersect two maps, combining the values for keys that appear in both maps using the given function.

`intersectionWith (-) (singleton 0 3) (singleton 0 2) == singleton 0 1`
declarations.title: intersectionWith

declarations.comments:
Compute the difference of two maps, that is a new map of all the
mappings in the left map that do not have a corresponding key in
the right map.
declarations.title: difference

declarations.comments:
This newtype provides a `Semigroup` instance for `HashMap k v`
which delegates to the `Semigroup v` instance of elements.

We are currently in step 1 of the following migration process:
1. Add `SemigroupHashMap` with the new `Semigroup` instance and remove old instance from `HashMap`.

   The new instance uses `unionWith append` instead of `union`.
   You can recover the previous, left-biased behaviour by using
   `SemigroupHashMap k (First v)` in place of `HashMap k v`.

2. Add new `Semigroup` instance to `HashMap` and deprecate `SemigroupHashMap`.
3. Remove `SemigroupHashMap`.
declarations.title: SemigroupHashMap

declarations.comments:
Remove duplicates from an array.

Like `nub` from `Data.Array`, but uses a `Hashable` constraint
instead of an `Ord` constraint.
declarations.title: nubHash

children.comments:
The `Foldable` instance is best used with a *commutative*
function/`Monoid`, since hash sets do not guarantee any
particular order.
children.title: foldableHashSet

declarations.comments:
A `HashSet a` is a set with elements of type `a`.

`a` needs to be `Hashable` for most operations.
declarations.title: HashSet

declarations.comments: The empty set.
declarations.title: empty

declarations.comments: The singleton set.
declarations.title: singleton

declarations.comments: Insert a value into a set.
declarations.title: insert

declarations.comments: Test whether a value is in a set.
declarations.title: member

declarations.comments: Remove a value from a set.
declarations.title: delete

declarations.comments:
Construct a new set by applying a function to each element of an
input set.

If distinct inputs map to the same output, this changes the
cardinality of the set, therefore hash set is not a `Functor`.
Also, the order in which elements appear in the new set is
entirely dependent on the hash function for type `b`.
declarations.title: map

declarations.comments:
Remove all elements from the set for which the predicate does not
hold.

`filter (const false) s == empty`
declarations.title: filter

declarations.comments: Map a function over a set, keeping only the `Just` values.
declarations.title: mapMaybe

declarations.comments: Union two sets.
declarations.title: union

declarations.comments: Union a collection of sets.
declarations.title: unions

declarations.comments: Intersect two sets.
declarations.title: intersection

declarations.comments:
Difference of two sets.

Also known as set minus or relative complement. Returns a set of
all elements of the left set that are not in the right set.
declarations.title: difference

declarations.comments:
Count the number of elements.

Also known as cardinality, or length.
declarations.title: size

declarations.comments:
Test whether a set is empty.

`isEmpty s  ==  (s == empty)`
declarations.title: isEmpty

declarations.comments:
Turn an array into a hash set.

This uses a mutable hash map internally and is faster than
`fromFoldable`.
declarations.title: fromArray

declarations.comments: Create a set from a foldable structure.
declarations.title: fromFoldable

declarations.comments:
Turn a set into an array of its elments in no particular order.

To delete duplicates in an array, consider using `nubHash` from
`Data.HashMap` instead of `toArray <<< fromFoldable`.
declarations.title: toArray

declarations.comments:
Turn a set into an unfoldable functor.

You probably want to use `toArray` instead, especially if you
want to get an array out.
declarations.title: toUnfoldable

declarations.comments:
The `Hashable` type class represents types with decidable
equality and a hash function for use in hash-based algorithms and
data structures, not cryptography.

Instances of `Hashable` must satisfy the following law:

```PureScript
(a == b) `implies` (hash a == hash b)
```

Note that while `hash = const 0` is a law-abiding implementation,
one would usually prefer more discrimination. Hash-based data
structures and algorithms tend to perform badly in the presence
of excessive numbers of collisions.

Hash values produced by `hash` should not be relied upon to be
stable accross multiple executions of a program and should not be
stored externally. While we currently do not do this, we might
want to use a fresh salt for every execution in the future.
declarations.title: Hashable
